### 5.1 Designated Director

#### 5.1.1 Appointment

In accordance with Rule 2(1)(ba) of the PML Rules and Paragraph 3.1 of the 2026 Guidelines, the Company has designated a Designated Director ("DD") who is responsible for ensuring overall compliance with the obligations imposed under Chapter IV of the PMLA and the PML Rules.

The name, designation, address, and contact details of the Designated Director shall be communicated promptly to FIU-IND in accordance with Rule 7(1) of the PML Rules. Any change shall be updated through the FINGate portal within seven (7) days.

#### 5.1.2 Responsibilities of the Designated Director

In accordance with Paragraphs 3.1.1 through 3.1.5 of the 2026 Guidelines, the Designated Director shall:

(a) **Record-keeping mechanism (Paragraph 3.1.1):** Evolve an internal mechanism for adherence to the procedures and manner of maintaining information in accordance with Rule 5 of the PML Rules, including proper upkeep of CDD records, transaction records, and documents required under PMLA and PML Rules;

(b) **Information-furnishing mechanism (Paragraph 3.1.2):** Evolve an internal mechanism for adherence to the procedure and manner of furnishing information to FIU-IND in accordance with Rule 7 of the PML Rules;

(c) **Timely submission of reports (Paragraph 3.1.3):** Ensure timely and accurate submission in respect of transactions prescribed under Rule 3 of the PML Rules, any reports prescribed by FIU-IND, and information sought by FIU-IND under Section 12A of the PMLA;

(d) **Risk assessment (Paragraph 3.1.4):** Ensure that risk assessment is carried out as prescribed under Rule 9(13) of the PML Rules to identify, assess, and take effective measures to mitigate ML/TF/PF risks;

(e) **Oversight of compliance culture (Paragraph 3.1.5):** Oversee and ensure that officers and employees of the Company follow all compliance procedures relating to record-keeping, CDD, transaction monitoring, and reporting mandated under Chapter IV of the PMLA and the PML Rules. The Designated Director shall ensure that adequate resources, internal controls, processes, and training are in place to support statutory AML/CFT/CPF compliance.

#### 5.1.3 Supplementary Responsibilities for Listed Entity

As the Company is a listed entity, the Designated Director shall additionally:

(a) Ensure that AML/CFT/CPF-related disclosures, where material, are reflected in the Company's periodic regulatory filings;

(b) Coordinate with the Audit Committee on AML/CFT/CPF compliance matters and on the findings of the independent annual audit conducted under Section 8.3 of this Policy;

(c) Ensure that the Board's oversight of AML/CFT/CPF compliance is documented in Board minutes in a manner consistent with applicable listing regulations and Companies Act requirements.

#### 5.2.2 Minimum Requirements and Qualifications of the Principal Officer

In accordance with Paragraph 3.2 of the 2026 Guidelines (which incorporates and codifies the erstwhile Guidance for Principal Officer dated February 25, 2025), the Principal Officer shall meet the following minimum requirements and qualifications:

(a) **Exclusive engagement (Paragraph 3.2(a)):** The PO shall be exclusively engaged with the Company on a full-time basis and shall not undertake any simultaneous or concurrent engagement with any other entity in any capacity;

(b) **Seniority and authority (Paragraph 3.2(b)):** The PO shall have sufficient level of seniority and authority within the organisation hierarchy to act independently without interference, bureaucratic constraints, or improper influences;

(c) **Knowledge and experience (Paragraph 3.2(c)):** The PO shall be familiar with AML/CFT/CPF legal requirements, reporting obligations, and enforcement mechanisms, and shall have relevant experience of a minimum of three (3) years with the appropriate skill set to fulfil obligations under PMLA, PML Rules, and associated regulations;

(d) **Sectoral knowledge (Paragraph 3.2(d)):** The PO shall have thorough knowledge of ML/TF risks and vulnerabilities relevant to the Company and to the VDA and VDA SP sector. The PO shall also be aware of emerging ML/TF trends and typologies;

(e) **Permanent invitee to risk committees (Paragraph 3.2(e)):** The PO shall be a permanent invitee to high-level committee(s) which evaluate risks associated with products and services, to ensure that ML/TF risks posed by different products, services, transactions, clients, geographic areas, etc. are appropriately identified, assessed, and mitigated;

(f) **Resources and access (Paragraph 3.2(f)):** The PO shall have sufficient resources, including adequate support staff with necessary expertise, technical resources, and unhindered and timely access to relevant information pertaining to client identification, Client Due Diligence information, transaction records, and other relevant information, to ensure effective monitoring, reporting, and implementation of the AML/CFT/CPF program;

(g) **Internal guidelines for information access (Paragraph 3.2(g)):** The Company shall have appropriate internal guidelines to enforce timelines and compliance in making available to the PO any information, documents, etc. from relevant authorities within the organisation, to enable the PO to respond promptly to requests for information made by FIU-IND, law enforcement agencies, or regulators;

(h) **Quarterly Board reporting (Paragraph 3.2(h)):** The PO shall place a review/status of the AML/CFT/CPF function before the Board or a Board-level sub-committee, preferably on a quarterly basis;

(i) **India-based (Paragraph 3.2(i)):** The PO shall be based in India to ensure effective discharge of obligations under the PMLA framework;

(j) **No conflict of interest (Paragraph 3.2(j)):** To avoid conflict of interest, the PO shall be exclusively engaged for responsibilities cast under Chapter IV of the PMLA and shall not be actively involved in business or operational activities of the Company;

(k) **Separation from Designated Director:** The Principal Officer and the Designated Director shall be separate individuals;

(l) **Communication to FIU-IND:** As per Rule 7(1) of the PML Rules, the name, designation, address, and contact details of both the PO and the DD shall be communicated promptly to FIU-IND and shall be updated through the FINGate portal.

#### 5.2.3 Roles and Responsibilities of the Principal Officer

In accordance with Paragraph 3.3 of the 2026 Guidelines, the Principal Officer shall be responsible for:

(a) **Overall compliance and reporting (Paragraph 3.3):** Ensuring compliance, monitoring transactions, and sharing and reporting information as required under the PMLA and the PML Rules;

(b) **Furnishing prescribed transaction information (Paragraph 3.3(b)):** As prescribed under Rule 7(2) of the PML Rules, furnishing the information referred to in Rule 3(1) of the PML Rules to FIU-IND on the basis of information available with the Company. A copy of such information shall be retained for the purposes of official record;

(c) **Furnishing suspicious transaction information (Paragraph 3.3(c)):** As prescribed under Rule 8(2) of the PML Rules, on being satisfied that a transaction is suspicious, furnishing the information promptly to FIU-IND;

(d) **Internal mechanism for suspicious transactions (Paragraph 3.3(d)):** Evolving and implementing an internal mechanism, with regard to any directions and guidelines issued by FIU-IND, for furnishing information as prescribed under Rule 3(1) of the PML Rules. Special attention shall be paid to all complex, unusual large transactions, and all unusual patterns of transactions which have no apparent economic or visible lawful purpose. The background, including all documents, office records, and memoranda pertaining to such transactions, and the purpose thereof, shall be examined, and the findings at PO level shall be properly recorded. Such records and related documents shall be made available to relevant authorities, as required. These records shall be preserved for five (5) years as required under PMLA;

(e) **Ultimate decision-making on alerts (Paragraph 3.3(e)):** While the activities of analysing alerts and preparing documents for managing alerts may be delegated within the AML compliance team, the ultimate analysis and decision-making rests with the PO. The records verified by and papers related to this decision shall be recorded and retained for audits;

(f) **Recording grounds for suspicion (Paragraph 3.3(f)):** The PO shall record reasons for treating any transaction or series of transactions as suspicious. There shall be no undue delay in arriving at such a conclusion once a suspicious transaction is escalated to the PO;

(g) **Decision on closure of alerts (Paragraph 3.3(g)):** Where the PO is of the opinion that a transaction is not reportable, the decision on closure of the alert shall be taken by the PO, and the reasons for not reporting such transactions shall be clearly recorded;

(h) **Review of alert lists and approach (Paragraph 3.3(h)):** The PO shall review the list of alerts and the approach from time to time to ensure that the reporting mechanism is complete and in line with expectations. The PO shall conduct surprise checks of the data being monitored by the AML compliance unit, and check transactions on a sample basis, to ensure there is no gap and that all unusual/potential suspicious transactions have been highlighted to the PO on an ongoing basis;

(i) **Timely access to information (Paragraph 3.3(i)):** The PO and the staff assisting in execution of AML/CFT guidelines shall have timely access to information including customer identification data, other KYC information, and records;

(j) **Board reporting (Paragraph 3.3):** The PO appointed for AML/CFT/CPF compliance shall report directly to the Board or a designated Committee of the Board. The PO shall, on a periodic basis (and/or at the frequency determined by the Board, but not later than one year), report at minimum the following items:

   i. Assessment of the effectiveness of the Company's AML/CFT/CPF compliance program;

   ii. Any identified risks or vulnerabilities in the program;

   iii. Summary of Suspicious Transaction Reports (STRs), other reports prescribed in PMLA/PML Rules, and any other information/reports prescribed by FIU-IND, submitted to FIU-IND;

   iv. Any instructions, red-flag indicators, typologies, guidance, etc. issued by FIU-IND from time to time, and their implementation status;

   v. Any proposed changes to the AML/CFT/CPF policy of the Company.

### 5.3 AML/CFT/CPF Compliance Function

Given the Company's current scale, the AML/CFT/CPF function is led directly by the Principal Officer. As the Company's operations grow, the Principal Officer shall recommend to the Board the expansion of the compliance function into a dedicated team in line with the scale and complexity of the Company's transactions and customer base.

The Principal Officer shall ensure that, even in a single-officer compliance function, the following responsibilities are clearly discharged:

(a) Customer onboarding KYC review and escalation of high-risk cases;

(b) Transaction monitoring alert review and escalation;

(c) Sanctions screening alert review and disposition;

(d) STR drafting and filing;

(e) Periodic CDD refresh for existing customers;

(f) Maintenance of records under Rule 5 of the PML Rules.

Where required, the Principal Officer shall engage external specialist support (subject to confidentiality protections and compliance with the PML framework) to supplement in-house capacity.

### 5.3 AML/CFT/CPF Compliance Team

The Company maintains a dedicated AML/CFT/CPF compliance team reporting to the Principal Officer. The team includes personnel responsible for:

(a) Customer onboarding KYC review and escalation of high-risk cases;

(b) Transaction monitoring alert review and escalation;

(c) Sanctions screening alert review and disposition;

(d) STR drafting and filing;

(e) Periodic CDD refresh for existing customers;

(f) Maintenance of records under Rule 5 of the PML Rules.

All compliance team members shall undergo AML/CFT/CPF training upon onboarding and at least annually thereafter, in accordance with Paragraph 4.3 of the 2026 Guidelines and Section 9 of this Policy. Specific roles, responsibilities, and reporting lines within the team shall be documented in the Company's internal compliance team organogram.

### 5.3 AML/CFT/CPF Compliance Function

The Company maintains a multi-function AML/CFT/CPF compliance organisation reporting to the Principal Officer. The compliance organisation is structured into specialised sub-functions, each with its own leadership and reporting lines:

(a) **Customer Due Diligence and Onboarding:** Responsible for KYC review at onboarding, document verification, beneficial ownership identification, and risk classification at the point of relationship establishment;

(b) **Transaction Monitoring:** Responsible for alert generation review, investigation, and escalation. Includes both rule-based monitoring and behavioural analytics;

(c) **Sanctions Screening:** Responsible for sanctions list management, screening operations, alert disposition, and coordination with relevant authorities on sanctions matches;

(d) **Suspicious Transaction Reporting:** Responsible for STR drafting, internal review, Principal Officer escalation, and post-filing record-keeping;

(e) **Periodic Review and CDD Refresh:** Responsible for periodic KYC updation, risk classification review (per Paragraph 3.6.2(c) of the 2026 Guidelines), and enhanced due diligence on triggered cases;

(f) **Regulatory Liaison:** Responsible for FIU-IND coordination, Section 12A response coordination, regulatory inquiry management, and report submissions;

(g) **AML Technology and Data:** Responsible for the compliance technology stack, including transaction monitoring systems, sanctions screening tools, blockchain analytics platforms, and case management systems.

All members of the compliance organisation shall undergo AML/CFT/CPF training upon onboarding and at least annually thereafter, in accordance with Paragraph 4.3 of the 2026 Guidelines and Section 9 of this Policy. Sub-function leaders shall report to the Principal Officer with appropriate escalation paths defined for high-risk cases.
